		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>Who wants a $32,000 copy of <em> Runaway Bunny </em>?</h1>
		<h2>Field notes from a visit to the Antiquarian Book Fair.</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/brittanyallen/"  title="Brittany Allen">Brittany Allen</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">May 1, 2026</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p class="p2">This weekend, the Park Avenue Armory plays host to the <a href="https://www.nyantiquarianbookfair.com/" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">New York Antiquarian Book Fair</span></a>—i.e., Mecca, for a certain type of bibliophile.</p>
<p class="p2">At the press preview, I&#8217;m conspicuously underdressed, having (lazily) assumed bowties and sweater-vests would rule the day in this crowd. Instead, it&#8217;s a sea of chic blue suits. Multiple dealers arrive in sequined floor-length cocktail dresses. At the Bruce McKittrick Rare Books Booth, all the purveyors wear flowered headbands.</p>
<p class="p2">Visitors skew more eccentric. Leaning against the Armory entrance, I spy a fellow in cowboy hat and bright chartreuse pants. Which is all to tee up my first question: who<i> are</i> these people?</p>
<span class="caption"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="271002" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/who-wants-a-32000-copy-of-runaway-bunny/la-woman/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1920,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.6&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 15&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1777569937&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;5.96&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0083333333333333&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="LA Woman" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;A rare Eve Babitz.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-768x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-271002 size-large" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="768" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-225x300.jpg 225w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-45x60.jpg 45w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-1536x2048.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-38x50.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/LA-Woman-scaled.jpg 1920w" sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /> A rare Eve Babitz.</span>
<p class="p2">The first fair patron I spoke to—in a dapper newsboy cap—was Jeanne Hilary, a self-identified cartographer and the founder of <a href="https://bicycleutopia.io/" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">Bicycle Utopia.</span></a> An independent historian, Hilary makes maps of Gotham’s under-examined corridors. (“All five boroughs,” she confirms, with no small pride.) She tells me she’s visiting the show to seek out sites of interest for her city guides project.</p>
<p class="p2">On the trading floor, the world is represented. I spy sellers from Paris, London, Copenhagen, Milan, Stockholm, and Vienna. At the Illinois based <a href="https://www.jhbooks.com/" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">Jeff Hirsch Books </span></a>booth, I receive a short history of the broadside, a bygone book party favor co-proprietor Susie Hirsch refers to as the “‘Would you like fries with that?'&#8221; of readings.&#8221;</p>
<p class="p2">Wandering the grid, I catch myself looking for themes. Jurisdictions. But the collector with an extremely narrow specialty seems, well, rare. Of the 200 dealers represented, the majority pursue a wide mandate—everything from a general “Antiquity” to “African Americana, Cookbooks, Ephemera, and Medicine,” in one case.</p>
<p class="p2">Here at <a href="https://www.baumanrarebooks.com/about-us/locations.aspx?location=newyork&amp;gad_source=1&amp;gad_campaignid=23321424186&amp;gbraid=0AAAAAD_tWSQdUQm7T1_nVpaQAgxuXUOJH&amp;gclid=CjwKCAjwntHPBhAaEiwA_Xp6Rm29Qsdf81EH_Qw7MoEHOFE14_UN3QDxOV0C4ksV_kQsF2s7IqhLGxoCfncQAvD_BwE" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Bauman Rare Books</a>, for instance, is a first edition <i>Runaway Bunny </i>($32k) spitting distance from a copy of Milton Friedman’s essays ($6500). It’s jarring to see these titles as they’d never be shelved, in such close proximity. But perhaps I’m just overwhelmed by the offerings. So many books, so little context.</p>
<p class="p2">The <a href="https://createsend.com/t/y-5EBAA6A64D66B2AC2540EF23F30FEDED" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">Harper’s</span></a> booth is an exception. When I’m caught ogling a signed Richard Hell and the Voidoids poster, apparently from a penultimate show ($2750) the proprietor tells me they went with a “pictures generation and downtown theme,&#8221; apparently counting on downtown nerds like this guy.</p>
<p class="p2">Another booth draws my eye with its display of pulpy paperbacks, all written to capitalize on the 60s “Beatnik craze.&#8221; I’ve lost Jeanne Hilary by this point, but I hope she finds this stall.</p>
<span class="caption"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="270995" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/who-wants-a-32000-copy-of-runaway-bunny/beatnik-booth/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.6&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 15&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1777567849&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;5.96&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;160&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.016666666666667&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="beatnik booth" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-1240x930.jpg" class="wp-image-270995 size-large" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-1240x930.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="930" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-1240x930.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-300x225.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-768x576.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-60x45.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/beatnik-booth-scaled-e1777639311814-50x38.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /> A selection of Beatnik pulp: a genuinely weird marketing trend.</span>
<p class="p2">Elsewhere, there&#8217;s antiquity. Lots of antiquity.</p>
<p class="p2">Here, the first printing of Euclid to be commissioned in Arabic ($88,500). I admit a genuine “ooh!” at the sight of a signed first edition of Shackleton’s “fascinating account of the British Antarctic Expedition of 1907-1909,” apparently “number 273 of only 300 copies printed.&#8221; That’s <em>also</em> going for $88,500. But this is by no means the high end of the spectrum, price-wise.</p>
<p class="p2">At Liber Antiquus, Early Books &amp; Manuscripts, a 16th century first edition “printed by England’s first printer, William Caxton,” is priced at $350k. The mind reels, the wallet screams, and I&#8217;m struck by a paradox: the vibe of the fair is curious, but the event itself is designed to transfer knowledge from public to private space. Which does run a little contra to the whole concept of<i> reading.</i></p>
<p class="p2">Given: books are fetish objects. I think this later, from my living room, where I sit at the foot of my own Mountain TBR. Books are fetish objects,<i> and</i> commodities—but what does it mean to grant them exorbitant monetary value? The fact that for a cool quarter million, a piece of history could be…well, not <i>mine</i>, but somebody’s? I can&#8217;t help but conjure the end of <i>Indiana Jones</i>, when the ark is wheeled into an anonymous warehouse.</p>
<p class="p2">Rare book dealing has rhymes with the <a href="https://news.artnet.com/market/how-the-art-world-became-the-art-industry-1710228" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">art market</span></a> in that we can trace its arc from eccentric hobby to a global luxury market. But another wrinkle: unlike visual art, most books aren&#8217;t designed for display. This gives the luxury collecting enterprise an ironic tint. You try to picture the dinner party where someone says, &#8220;Wanna see my Shackleford?&#8221; and everything comes up Causabon. For how do you admire an object you&#8217;re technically meant to <i>read</i>?</p>
<span class="caption"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="271003" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/who-wants-a-32000-copy-of-runaway-bunny/fred-roos-notes/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.6&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 15&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1777567377&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;5.96&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;50&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0033003300330033&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Fred Roos notes" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-1240x930.jpg" class="wp-image-271003 size-large" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-1240x930.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="930" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-1240x930.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-300x225.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-768x576.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-60x45.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Fred-Roos-notes-50x38.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /> Fred Roos&#8217; notes on <em>The Godfather.</em></span>
<p class="p2">With its abundant broadsides, maps, and mountable ephemera<b>, </b>the fair does answer this question—while providing a pleasant reminder that the very definition of &#8220;book&#8221; is slippery. The New World Cartographic stall is heavy with the obvious. At Manhattan Rare Books, where a fair bit of Hollywood ephemera is on display, one can peruse Fred Roos’ handwritten notes on an early screening of <i>The Godfather II. </i></p>
<p class="p2">And at <a href="https://www.fugitivematerials.com/" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">Fugitive Materials</span></a>, you can buy an OG Silence = Death sign—from ACT-UP’s first printed run of the slogan—for $50. Which seems<i> almost</i> reasonable. In the same glass case, issues of <i>Voice of the Lumpen</i>, the Black Panthers’ broadside, go for hundreds of dollars. Fascinating, moving, all this personal history, but I wonder again, who is the collector who needs these items? How are such things placed, in a human’s house?</p>
<p class="p2">Daylon Orr, the founder of <a href="https://www.fugitivematerials.com/about.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Fugitive</a>, assures me his mandate is civic-minded. He worked in book trade for a little over a decade and started dealing in 2020, and tells me the whole store&#8217;s mission is reparative/curatorial—he aims to collect and circulate “underground, oppositional, queer materials…broadly speaking, stuff that is underrepresented in the book world.”</p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="270996" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/who-wants-a-32000-copy-of-runaway-bunny/voice-of-the-lumpen/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.6&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 15&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1777568357&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;5.96&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;125&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.0083333333333333&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="voice of the lumpen" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-1240x930.jpg" class="wp-image-270996 size-large" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-1240x930.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="930" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-1240x930.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-300x225.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-768x576.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-60x45.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/voice-of-the-lumpen-scaled-e1777641452751-50x38.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /> Some of the ephemera from Fugitive Materials</span>
<p class="p2">Fugitive works closely with universities, libraries, and museums. They also serve as personal archivists. As is the case with the photographer <a href="https://www.donaannmcadams.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Dona Ann McAdams</a>, whose collection &#8220;Arresting Images&#8221; is on display.</p>
<p class="p2">Orr points these things out with a historian’s true enthusiasm. And yes, okay, sure, I’m seduced by this shot from Annie Sprinkle&#8217;s street wedding. Insanely, I reach for my wallet, thinking: I <i>do</i> want some of this history. To have and to hoard, like I was there.</p>
<p class="p2">The whole fair appeals to just this sensibility: the magpie collector, the time traveling nostalgist. From the recent and overlooked, to the ancient and obsolete.</p>
<p class="p2">The first German language edition of a book “written to quell the growing hysteria around the conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn in February 1524,” raises my novelist&#8217;s antennae. Still more manuscripts offer serious historical discoveries.</p>
<p class="p2">Somewhere in these stacks is a working dossier of Étienne Charavay, the handwriting expert whose analysis gave technical credibility to the prosecution in the Dreyfus Affai<b>r</b>. The marked text suggests that there was an effort to sway the man towards a predetermined conclusion. Something, perhaps, that should be in a museum. Or for the public, at least.</p>
<p class="p2">*</p>
<p class="p2">My favorite booth appears towards the end of my amble.</p>
<p class="p2">Here, the question of what-makes-a-book feels refreshingly beside the point. For Heide Hatry, a Heidelberg-born artist turned book dealer living on the Upper West Side, is interested in the porosity of the object. Book as aesthetic, and book as vehicle for story.</p>
<p class="p2">Her booth—<a href="https://sanctuaryrarebooks.com/" class="external" target="_blank"><span class="s1">Sanctuary Books</span></a>, of New York—draws your eye for featuring dresses made of pages. Which she made.</p>
<span class="caption"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="270994" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/who-wants-a-32000-copy-of-runaway-bunny/heide-dress/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1920,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.6&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 15&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1777569871&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;5.96&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;200&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.016666666666667&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Heide Dress" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;One of Heide&amp;#8217;s creations.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-768x1024.jpg" class="wp-image-270994 size-large" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="768" height="1024" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-225x300.jpg 225w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-45x60.jpg 45w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-1536x2048.jpg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-38x50.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Heide-Dress-scaled.jpg 1920w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /> One of Hatry&#8217;s creations.</span>
<p class="p3">She shows me another personal project, a series of sculptures made in homage to the late <a href="https://nycbirdalliance.org/blog/the-year-of-flaco-new-exhibition-chronicles-famous-nyc-owl-s-impact" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Flaco the Owl</a>, who she called a friend. From the found material of many tiny old books, Hatry&#8217;s assembled a physical elegy. A book of books, serving a highly specialized purpose. Which strikes me as one of the more precious and personal finds on the floor.</p>
<p class="p2">I try to picture the dinner party where someone says &#8220;hey, come check this out!&#8221; and think: I would. Then I realize: I <em>have.</em> And it&#8217;s been a lovely day at the fair.</p>
